### User:
what does this command do: ssh -i "~/UserKey.pem" -C -L 25900:localhost:5900 user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com

### Response:


This command is used to establish an SSH connection between your local machine and a remote server using the Amazon Web Services (AWS) instance. 

The `ssh` command is used for secure shell access over port 22. The `-i` option specifies the private key file to use for authentication, and the `-C` option disables the X11 forwarding. 

The `user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com` is the IP address or hostname of the AWS instance that you want to connect to. The port number, `25900`, specifies the local port on your machine that SSH will listen for incoming connections. 

The `-L` option lists the local port number and the remote server's port number in the format `local_port:remote_server_port`. This allows you to establish an SSH connection between your local machine and the AWS instance using a single command.
